The primary purpose of control AU-2 (Event Logging) is to identify, specify, and coordinate the types of events that a system is capable of logging in order to support the audit function and guide after-the-fact investigations of incidents [3]. Specifically, it requires organizations to:
* Identify the types of events the system is capable of logging to support the audit function [3];
* Coordinate the event logging function with other organizational entities requiring audit-related information to guide selection criteria [3];
* Specify the subset of event types to be logged along with the frequency or situation requiring logging [3];
* Provide a rationale explaining why the selected event types are adequate to support after-the-fact investigations of incidents [3]; and
* Review and update the selected event types at an organization-defined frequency to ensure they remain relevant and continue to support organizational needs [3].

FIPS 199 defines the security objectives as confidentiality, integrity, and availability [1][3][6]. 

Under SP 800-53 control AC-2, organizations must satisfy the following account management requirements:
* Define and document the types of accounts allowed and specifically prohibited for use within the system [13];
* Assign account managers [13];
* Require organization-defined prerequisites and criteria for group and role membership [13];
* Specify authorized users of the system, group and role membership, and access authorizations (privileges) and organization-defined attributes (as required) for each account [13];
* Require approvals by organization-defined personnel or roles for requests to create accounts [13];
* Create, enable, modify, disable, and remove accounts in accordance with organization-defined policy, procedures, prerequisites, and criteria [13];
* Monitor the use of accounts [13];
* Notify account managers and organization-defined personnel or roles within organization-defined time periods when accounts are no longer required, when users are terminated or transferred, and when system usage or need-to-know changes for an individual [13];
* Authorize access to the system based on a valid access authorization, intended system usage, and organization-defined attributes (as required) [13];
* Review accounts for compliance with account management requirements at an organization-defined frequency [13];
* Establish and implement a process for changing shared or group account authenticators (if deployed) when individuals are removed from the group [13]; and
* Align account management processes with personnel termination and transfer processes [13].

